    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Hopedene | Surrey</placeName>
                    <date>June 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>My dear G.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your letter has told us a lot of interesting news.— I am extremely glad that your work is coming to a satisfactory end. Its value I expect under a <hi rend="underline">geological</hi> point of view is mainly negative, as Geologists require a much greater change of climate within a rather recent period.— There were Luxuriant forests in Spitbergen during the middle Tertiary period.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>There is a map in Wallace’s new book on Geographical Distribution, showing depth of sea according to all recent data &amp; a calculation of its average depth viz 12,000 ft.— Humboldt estimated average height of land at 1000 ft. See p. 36 &amp; 37 of this book.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I think the most interesting &amp; probable supposition w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be to submerge in the N. <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> or <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> hemisphere taking St George’s Channel<ref target="#foot.f4"/> as centre of subsidence to depth of 12000 ft, &amp; raise at the antipodes <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> or <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> of hemisphere (where ever there is water) to height of 1000 ft &amp; see the result.— There is reason to suspect that there has been great &amp; recent subsidence in Antarctic region &amp; near N. Zealand.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>I hardly dare venture to hope that your astronomical problem about obliquity &amp;c will really work.<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>Your affect. | C. Darwin</p>
<p>Frank has made a really fine zoological discovery.—<ref target="#foot.f7"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
